    <h2 id="section-6">6. Case law and personal data</h2>

    <details>
        <summary>What does the case law database contain?</summary>
        <div><p>The case law database contains published judicial decisions from Belgian courts, sourced from JuPortal. All decisions are automatically pseudonymised before publication on our platform.</p></div>
    </details>

    <details>
        <summary>What does pseudonymisation of judgments mean?</summary>
        <div>
            <p>We process all judicial decisions automatically using Named Entity Recognition (NER) in Dutch and French. This system:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Replaces personal names with initials</strong> &mdash; e.g. "Jan Peeters" becomes "J. P."</li>
                <li><strong>Removes or masks</strong> email addresses, phone numbers, national register numbers and IBAN numbers</li>
            </ul>
            <p>As a result, in most judgments you will see only initials instead of full names.</p>
        </div>
    </details>

    <details>
        <summary>I recognise my initials in a judgment. Are those my personal data?</summary>
        <div>
            <p>When you find initials in a judgment (e.g. "J. P."), this is the result of our pseudonymisation. Initials alone are generally not directly identifiable to a natural person. However, they do constitute a <strong>pseudonym</strong> within the meaning of the GDPR: combined with the surrounding context of the judgment (date, court, facts), a party involved may potentially recognise themselves.</p>
            <p>If you recognise yourself in a pseudonymised judgment and wish it to be further modified or removed from the platform, you can submit a request (see below).</p>
        </div>
    </details>

    <details>
        <summary>I found my full name in a judgment. How is that possible?</summary>
        <div>
            <p>Despite our automatic NER processing, it can happen that certain names were not correctly detected and therefore <strong>not pseudonymised</strong>. This can occur with:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Unusual name structures or spellings</li>
                <li>Names that coincide with common words</li>
                <li>Technical processing errors when parsing the original document</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>We regret this.</strong> It is a shortcoming of the automated process, not a deliberate choice. You can submit a removal request and we will mask your data as soon as possible.</p>
        </div>
    </details>

    <details>
        <summary>How do I request removal of my personal data from a judgment?</summary>
        <div>
            <p>Send an email to <a href="mailto:privacy@wetwijzer.be">privacy@wetwijzer.be</a> with:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Your name</li>
                <li>The ECLI number of the judgment (found at the top of the judgment on our website)</li>
                <li>A description of the personal data found (initials, full name, address, etc.)</li>
            </ul>
            <p>We process your request within <strong>30 days</strong> in accordance with Art. 17 GDPR. Possible measures include:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Additional pseudonymisation of remaining personal data</li>
                <li>Complete removal of the judgment from our platform</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="small">We are not the original publisher of the judgment. Removal from our platform does not mean the judgment is removed from the original source (JuPortal). For removal at source, you should contact the relevant court or JuPortal.</p>
        </div>
    </details>

    <details>
        <summary>Why are judgments not indexed by search engines?</summary>
        <div>
            <p>Judicial decisions contain potentially sensitive personal data. Although the case law database is freely accessible to everyone, we take the following measures to handle this data responsibly:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Judgments are not indexed by search engines (noindex, robots.txt)</li>
                <li>All judgments are automatically pseudonymised (NER)</li>
                <li>In case of abuse, access can be revoked</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </details>

    <h2 id="section-7">7. Privacy and data protection</h2>

    <details>
        <summary>What data does WetWijzer collect?</summary>
        <div>
            <p>We collect minimal data:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Without account:</strong> standard server logs (IP address, User-Agent) for security purposes, retained for 90 days. When using the chatbot anonymously, an encrypted quota cookie (<code>_ww_anon</code>) is set that stores only the week number and number of questions asked — no personal data. <strong>No localStorage, sessionStorage or other browser persistence is used.</strong> After your visit, no trace is left in your browser.</li>
                <li><strong>With account:</strong> email address, optional name, language preference, credit usage, bookmarks and UI preferences (server storage)</li>
                <li><strong>Chatbot usage:</strong> metadata only (legal domain, language, intelligence level, credits). Never the content of your questions.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>See our full <a href="/privacy-policy">privacy policy</a>.</p>
        </div>
    </details>

    <details>
        <summary>Can the administrator see what I ask the chatbot?</summary>
        <div>
            <div><p><strong>No.</strong> Our analytics database (<code>chatbot_analytics</code>) contains no column for question text. Your question is processed in server memory only long enough to send it to Azure, then discarded. A one-way <strong>SHA-256 hash</strong> (truncated to 12 characters) is logged for debugging — this is irreversible and cannot be used to reconstruct your question. The operator can only see <em>that</em> a question was asked, in which legal domain and in which language.</p></div>
            <div><p><strong>Exception — Report:</strong> When you click the <em>Report</em> (🚩) button on a response, both your question and the answer are sent to the administrator for quality review. This is clearly indicated in the interface before you confirm. Reporting is entirely voluntary.</p></div>
        </div>
    </details>

    <details>
        <summary>Does WetWijzer use cookies?</summary>
        <div>
            <p>When you are logged in, a session cookie is set (<code>_wetwijzer_session</code>) to maintain your login. When using the <strong>anonymous chatbot</strong> (without an account, from Belgium), an encrypted quota cookie (<code>_ww_anon</code>) is set that only tracks how many questions you have asked this week — it contains no personal data and is automatically deleted after 8 days.</p>
            <p><strong>No browser storage:</strong> WetWijzer does not use localStorage, sessionStorage or similar techniques. Non-logged-in visitors leave no trace in the browser whatsoever. We do not use tracking cookies, advertising cookies or Google Analytics.</p>
            <p>For website statistics we use Umami, a privacy-friendly open-source solution that places no cookies and collects no personal data.</p>
        </div>
    </details>

    <details>
        <summary>Where is my data stored?</summary>
        <div>
            <p>All your data is processed within the EU/EEA:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Application servers:</strong> Germany (Hetzner)</li>
                <li><strong>AI processing (standard):</strong> Sweden (Azure OpenAI)</li>
                <li><strong>Payments:</strong> Ireland (Stripe)</li>
                <li><strong>Email:</strong> Switzerland (Migadu, adequacy decision)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </details>

    <details>
        <summary>What are my rights under the GDPR?</summary>
        <div>
            <p>You have the right to access, rectification, erasure, restriction, portability and objection. You can exercise these rights by sending an email to <a href="mailto:info@wetwijzer.be">info@wetwijzer.be</a> or by deleting your account via the account page. We respond within 30 days.</p>
            <p>You may also file a complaint with the <a href="https://www.dataprotectionauthority.be">Belgian Data Protection Authority</a>.</p>
        </div>
    </details>

